'''Alexander Hamilton''' (before 1688 – after 1733) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Captain (naval)|sea captain]], [[privateer]] and [[merchant]].

==Biography==
In his early years he travelled widely through [[Europe]], the [[Barbary coast]], the [[West Indies]], [[British India|India]] and [[South-east Asia]]. On his arrival in [[Bombay]] in 1688 he was briefly pressed into the employ of the [[British East India Company]] in a local war, and then set up as a private country trader, operating from [[Surat]]. He was appointed commander of the [[History of the Indian Navy|Bombay Marine]] in June 1717, in which post he suppressed [[piracy]].

The main extant source of information on Hamilton is his own book, ''[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.503139 A New Account of the East Indies]'' (1727). The term then covered a much wider geographic area than it does today - 'most of the countries and islands of commerce and navigation, between the [[Cape of Good Hope]] and the island of [[Japan]].' Illustrated with lively anecdotes, it provides a valuable insight into life in early modern [[Asia]].<ref>Tony Ballantyne, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/12042 ‘Hamilton, Alexander (b. before 1688, d. in or after 1733)’], Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004, accessed 1 Sept 2008.</ref>

