{{Infobox person |name = Ekrem Bardha |image = |caption = Political Conference |birth_place = [[Kolonje]], [[Albania]] |title = [[Activist]], [[Businessman]] }}
'''Ekrem Bardha''' (born 13 May 1933) is an [[Albanian American]] businessman, leader of the [[Albanian National Front]] in Michigan ([[Balli Kombëtar]]), co-founder of the [[National Albanian American Council]] (NAAC), and former owner of [[Illyria Newspaper]].<ref name="Illyria">{{cite web |url=http://www.illyriapress.com/about_us.php |accessdate=5 June 2010 |quote=Seven years later, Ekrem Bardha, another activist and businessman, became the owner of the newspaper. |title=Illyria – The true voice of the Albanians in America |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527193214/http://www.illyriapress.com/about_us.php |archivedate=27 May 2010 |df= }}</ref> He is currently serving as Albania's [[Honorary Consul]] in [[Michigan]]<ref name=hon-consul>{{cite web |title=Consular and Other Offices: The Embassy of the Republic of Albania |url=http://www.embassy.org/embassies/al-other.html#Michigan |website=embassy.org |publisher=Stapleton-Gray & Associates, Inc. |accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref> and is regarded as one of the most successful Albanians in America.<ref name="bbc">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/albanian/regionalnews/2008/05/080521_ekrem_bardha.shtml|date=21 May 2008|accessdate=5 June 2010|publisher=[[BBC]]|title=Ekrem Bardha biznesmen në Amerikë|language=Albanian}}</ref>
==Early life== Bardha was born in the southern village of [[Radanj]] in [[Kolonjë District]], [[Albania]]. Having escaped from the strict Albanian communist regime in 1953, after one of his brothers was jailed for political reasons, he settled in [[Detroit]] and went into the restaurant business. He eventually became the owner of 18 [[McDonald's]] fast-food franchises, which grossed over $25 million a year.<ref name="mcdonalds">{{cite web|url=http://www.luxner.com/cgi-bin/view_article.cgi?articleID=614|title=Golden Arches to Rise in Tiranë|date=29 September 1995|accessdate=5 July 2010|quote=Bardha, the owner of McDonald's restaurants in the Detroit area, wants to see the Golden Arches tower over Tiranë as well.}}</ref>
==Political activity== {{BLP unsourced section|date=December 2015}} Bardha, with congressman [[William Broomfield]] and others, contributed to the saving of arrested political activist [[Pjeter Ivezaj]] in [[Montenegro]] and was the reason the US threatened Yugoslavias favored nation status if Ivezaj was not released. Congressman Broomfield and Bardha testified before a congressional human rights committee regarding human rights abuses in Serbia against ethnic Albanians. Bardha has a lifetime as a human rights activist and has met with eight of U.S. Presidents for the Albanian/Kosovo cause. President [[Nixon]] assured him in his own handwriting after a meeting that he will refuse the [[Northern Epirus|Greek ambitions]] in Albania at any cost. Bardha also met with President [[Bill Clinton]] before the [[1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombing]] of [[Serbia]] by [[NATO]] and was assured that [[Kosovo]] will be freed from Serbian oppression. <ref>The Albanians</ref>
