{{Infobox person | name = Martial Van Schelle | image = Martial Van Schelle (1923).jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1899|7|6}} | birth_place = [[Wortel|Hoogstraten]], [[Belgium]]<ref>Het wonderbare leven van Martial Van Schelle door Armand Huet</ref> | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1943|3|15|1899|7|6}} | death_place = [[Breendonk]], [[Belgium]] | nationality = [[Belgium|Belgian]] | other_names = Ti | known_for = Olympic competition | occupation = aviator, bobsledder, businessman, swimmer }} '''Martial Van Schelle''' (sometimes shown as '''Martial van Schelle''', 6 July 1899 &ndash; 15 March 1943) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[bobsled]]der, [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]], [[Aviation|aviator]], and [[business]]man who competed in both the [[Summer Olympics|Summer]] and [[Winter Olympics]] for Belgium from the early 1920s to the late 1930s. He was captured by the [[Nazi Germany|Nazis]] during [[World War II]] and executed in a [[Nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]].
==Early life== Born in 1899, Van Schelle spent the early part of his life in the [[United States]].<ref name=early>[http://www.forumeerstewereldoorlog.nl/viewtopic.php?t=2523&view=previous&sid=a53482e9bed21d7ead30a647555f0e55 Early life of Van Schelle.]{{nl icon}} - accessed 22 April 2008.</ref> Living in [[Chicago, Illinois]] from 1904 to 1918, he lost his mother Annie when she was killed aboard the [[RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] when it was sunk in 1915 by a [[German Empire|German]] [[U-boat]].<ref name=early/> This resulted in him joining the [[American Expeditionary Force]] which landed in France in 1918 as a [[doughboy]].<ref name=early/> Following the end of hostilities of [[World War I]], Van Schelle stayed over in [[Belgium]] to help the nation rebuild.<ref name=early/>
==Sporting career== Competing in three [[Summer Olympics]], Van Schelle's best finish was 10th in the [[Swimming at the 1924 Summer Olympics – Men's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|men's 4 × 200 m freestyle relay]] at [[Paris]] in [[1924 Summer Olympics|1924]].<ref>[http://users.skynet.be/hermandw/olymp/sqswimf1.html Men's 100 m freestyle results: 1920-36]</ref><ref>[http://users.skynet.be/hermandw/olymp/sqswimx2.html Men's 4 x 200 m freestyle results: 1920-36]</ref> Van Schelle<!-- Done interchangeably for technical reasons --> also participated in [[balloon (aircraft)|balloon]]ing in the [[Gordon Bennett Cup (ballooning)|Gordon Bennett Cup]] twice, finishing fifth in 1933<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010227221316/http://www.coupegordonbennett.org/results/1933.asp 1933 Gordon Bennett Cup results.] - accessed 21 April 2008.</ref> and seventh in 1938.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010427104833/http://www.coupegordonbennett.org/results/1938.asp 1938 Gordon Bennett Cup results] - accessed 21 April 2008.</ref> At the [[1936 Winter Olympics]] in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]], Van Schelle competed in [[bobsleigh]]. He finished fifth in the [[Bobsleigh at the 1936 Winter Olympics – Four-man|four-man competition]] and ninth in the [[Bobsleigh at the 1936 Winter Olympics – Two-man|two-man event]].<ref>[http://www.todor66.com/olim/1936w/Bobsleigh_Doubles.html 1936 bobsleigh two-man results]</ref><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/olim/1936w/Bobsleigh_Fours.html 1936 bobsleigh four-man results]</ref>
==Business career== Van Schelle owned a [[sporting goods]] store in [[Brussels]],<ref>[http://www.vanschelle.com/English/histoire.html Picture of Van Schelle and some of his activities.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717184745/http://www.vanschelle.com/English/histoire.html |date=17 July 2011 }} - accessed 22 April 2008.</ref> earning an [[United States|American]] patent for a [[tennis racket]] in 1935.<ref>[http://www.google.com/patents?id=kERrAAAAEBAJ&pg=PP2&lpg=PP2&dq=%22Martial+van+Schelle%22&source=web&ots=8JYsDChQTp&sig=wn_3s2VcHzsCp6df4mH6PJzEBQA&hl=en#PPP2,M1 Google.com information on Van Schelle's 1935 tennis racket patent.] - accessed 21 April 2008.</ref> He later became owner of two [[Ice rink]]s in [[Brussels]] between 1933 and 1935, remaining owner until he was arrested by the [[Nazi Germany|Nazis]] on 15 January 1943.<ref name=belhock>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071024210039/http://www.kbijf.be/history_disp.php?id=16&l=e Royal Belgian Ice Hockey Federation history] - accessed 21 April 2008.</ref>
==Death== Taken away to [[Fort Breendonk|Breendonk concentration camp]], Van Schelle was executed by shooting on 15 March 1943.<ref name=belhock/><ref>[http://www.getuigen.be/Getuigenis/Trido-Victor/Trido-Victor-nl/tkst.htm Trido, Victor (1944). ''Breendook''. Paris: J. Dupuis & Fils.]{{nl icon}} Features Van Schelle. - accessed 22 April 2008.</ref><ref name="WWII">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/friv/lists.cgi?id=65 |title=Olympians Who Were Killed or Missing in Action or Died as a Result of War |accessdate=24 July 2018 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>
